# Codebase navigation — use coldstart MCP tools

Before searching or opening files in an unfamiliar codebase, use the
coldstart MCP tools to orient yourself. This saves tokens and avoids
broad, speculative file reads.

## Lookup order

1. Call `get-overview` first — before any Glob, grep, or file read.
   - Tells you which domains exist, what files live in each, and how
     domains connect to each other.
   - Use `domain_filter` to zoom into one area (e.g. `"auth"`, `"payments"`).

2. Call `get-structure` instead of reading a file just to check its shape.
   - Returns exports, internal/external imports, line count, token estimate,
     and architectural role — at zero file-read cost.
   - Only read the full file if `get-structure` confirms it's relevant.

3. Call `trace-deps` instead of manually chasing import statements.
   - `direction="imports"` — what does this file depend on?
   - `direction="importers"` — what depends on this file? (impact analysis)
   - `depth=2` or `depth=3` for transitive chains.

## Preferred patterns

```
# Starting a new task in an unfamiliar area
get-overview → get-structure → read file (only if needed)

# Understanding how a component connects to the rest of the codebase
get-overview → trace-deps → read file (only if needed)

# Impact analysis before editing a file
trace-deps (direction="importers") → decide which callers to update
```

## When to fall back to grep/rg

Use grep or rg only when coldstart tools don't answer the question:
- Searching for a specific string or literal value inside file contents
- Looking for call sites of a function by name across the whole repo
- Coldstart index is stale and you need up-to-the-second accuracy

In all other cases, prefer coldstart tools first.
